author: yourmusiceducation
description: The 1960s were a decade of tremendous political and cultural change in the United States. The first of the baby boomers who were rock ‘n’ roll teenagers in the 1950s began to assume leadership roles throughout American society and they continue to impact society (our most recent two presidents were from this group born in the early 40s). Over in England, skiffle groups were all the rage and teens had sporadic access to American music. When post-war embargoes were lifted in 1959, British youth raced to buy guitars and start their own skiffle bands, copying the styles of their favorite British and American artists. But no British act had ever topped the US charts until Mr. Acker Bill’s unlikely clarinet solo “Stranger on the Shore” became the top-selling pop album of the year in 1962. The Tornados had a hit with Telstar that year, and then The Beatles had three straight #1 songs in 1964. From the on, the door was wide open. The second-most successful act of the 60s was The Supremes, who first topped the chart in 1964, and had back-and-forth hits along with The Beatles into the next decade. #musichistory #learnontiktok #music #oldschool #yourmusiceducation #60smusic #1960 #1961 #1962 #1963 #1964 #1965 #1966 #1967 #1968 #1969 #elvis #thebeatles #thesupremes #therollingstones #britishinvasion #ukmusic #usmusic

author: themissingself
description: 🧬GENDER ARGUMENT 🧜‍♂️ | It’s hard to believe how divisive the topic of gender has become. The plight of the of trans* community, to feel safe in their bodies, homes, and country, has somehow turned into the most controversial issue of our time. You’d think the attention on the issue would breed good conversation, but no. NOWHERE, across the entirety of the internet, could I find a reasonable debate about gender. That is why I made this video a bit longer than the others, I felt a sense of responsibility to capture the essence of what people on both sides would say to each other if they weren’t so angry all the time. I feel so much compassion towards the trans community, trying to lead a movement of unprecedented inclusion, and I also feel for all of the people that are confused by the incompleteness of its ideology. It’s ironic that the debate is about identity, considering the fact that both sides seem to have forgotten that they are not their identities. The real battle always seems to be waging within ourselves, between the self that has no description, and the costume that it wears so that others can describe us. I hope it doesn’t take too much v10/ence for all of us to see ourselves in each-other. | #gender #transition #identity  #themissingself #educational #debate #inclusion #man #woman #nonbinary

author: mathewssonya
description: The middle english long vowel U was split into two parts: a short vowel U and the glide Y. With the word february this created a phonoligical impossibiltiy, specifically in the vowel after the consonant cluster BR. Modern English phonological rules produce “febryuary” which speakers handle in different ways. Some drop the R. Some drop the Y. Lots of speakers add a wee pause to account for the R. Basically its very silly and we should all be saying Feverer oe Feverell. #february #romanempire #oldenglish #historytime #linguistics #etymology #etymologytiktok #mudmonth #february2024 #learnontiktok #themoreyouknow #middleenglish

author: geography_joe
description: Replying to @A.S. #greenscreen Looking at #Maine’s population map! Maine is the 9th least populous #state with 1,395,430 residents, and is the least densely populated state east of the #Mississippi #river. The #MaineWoods region is responsible for this extremely low density, but also the fact that much of Maine experiences very harsh, long winters, and that the state is the furthest #east in the country, bordering only one other state (#NewHampshire), but two #provinces in #Canada, #NewBrunswick and #Quebec. #Lubec is the easternmost place in the country, while #Eastport is the easternmost city. Maine’s largest #city is #Portland, with about 60,000 people in the city itself, and 550,000 in the #metro area, while #Lewiston is 2nd, and the Lewiston/#Auburn (or #LA) metro is second in the state with about 65,000 people. Next up is #Bangor, with around 30k, with the #UniversityofMaine located nearby in #Orono. #Augusta, Maine’s #capital, is the 3rd smallest #statecapital in the #US, with just 19,000 residents. Maine is famous for its #lobster production, catching 90% of the nation’s supply, as well as being 2nd in #maplesyrup production, while it is also the most forested state, most rural state, the state with the second-most #islands, and the state with the most #French speakers (as a % of total population) of any state, largely due to the #StJohnValley region in northern #AroostookCounty, which abuts the #Canadian border with New Brunswick. Aroostook, known as ‘#thecounty’ in Maine, also includes towns like #Caribou, #PresqueIsle, and #Houlton, and is larger than the state of #Connecticut, while neighboring #Piscataquis #county is the least populous in Maine with just 15,000 residents. Maine’s #UnorganizedTerritory, covering 1/2 of the states land area, is home to just 9,000 residents, or 0.6% of the state’s population. author: joshterryplays
description: Sometimes incredible people have no discipline and it's not because they're incapable. It's because they were controlled in the past, it turned out badly and they now have a bad relationship with the idea of control.  Someone controlled them, misused that power, made their life worse, and now the idea of being controlled is so uncomfortable they can't control themselves without feeling like they should rebel. Because if someone disciplines you and you get bad results, you can develop a belief that discipline itself is bad. To grow out of this, you have to be willing to follow a rule again. Even if it's only one you make for yourself, and have faith in it until it gets you a positive result.  Order has to become something beneficial so the commanding parts of your own mind become a loving helper and not a harmful unknown force. #selfdevelopment #motivation #mindset #discipline

description: Slovakian MEP Miroslav Radačovský raised eyebrows when he released a white dove in the European parliamentary chamber on Wednesday, in what he said was a symbol  of peace. author: thatsleepdoc
description: If we didn’t laugh, we’d cry. These milestones are based on CDC normal development timeline (except that last one of course). Please understand that normal development is a RANGE. And “normal” development is often dictated by 75% of children reaching that milestone by that age. Which leaves a large chunk of the population that will achieve it later, but it still normal. If your physician is not concerned, you should be reassured. And as @Dr. Mona recently pointed out, no one will ask your child about these milestones during their job interview.  There are also neuro-atypical children that will develop on their own timeline, whether that be due to HIE, autism, genetic changes, or a myriad of other conditions. They don’t care what the guidelines say and they don’t need to. They will achieve milestones at their own pace.  Our role as physicians and parents is to ensure they have opportunity to reach their maximum potential and thrive.

author: bardboytroy
description: Replying to @strelitziachi Edit: to be clear, HIMYM and Friends both used supplemental laughter on occasion in addition to their audiences. The primary laughter came from the audiences watching (in the ways described in the video), but like most other sitcoms with an audience - they added canned laughter when the reaction wasnt as much as they wanted (tho HIMYM, esp in later seasons, would use its own previous recordings). So yes you likely have heard the same distinctive laughs multiple times, but that is not where the majority of the laughter comes from.  This actually turned into a video almost equally about Friends as my example of a more traditional laugh track. Both have their pros and cons (Friends is arguably funnier and has less poorly aged jokes, while HIMYM is better written and has amazing attention to detail - all in part due to their different laugh tracks), but I think its just interesting to see how the laugh tracks existing effected the shows. #friends #himym #howimetyourmother #fyp #medialiteracy #analysis #interpretation #media

author: thatsleepdoc
description: For chronic insomnia, good sleep is not based on hacks. The foundation for insomnia is built on Cognitive Behavior Therapy for Insomnia (and cognitive shuffling can be considered a technique within CBTi toolkit to help minimize maladaptive thoughts and arousal in bed). CBTi is built on a foundation of good sleep hygiene. Even CBTi can't work if you're pounding 3 cups of coffee a day. Sleep hygiene and CBTi is built on a foundation of good mental health. It's vital to seek care for anxiety, depression, etc.
